```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Secure Social Security Number Entry</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            padding: 20px;
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333;
        }
        form {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            gap: 10px;
        }
        label {
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input[type="text"], input[type="submit"] {
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            width: 100%;
        }
        input[type="submit"] {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        input[type="submit"]:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .error {
            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Enter Your Social Security Number</h1>

<form id="ssnForm" method="post" action="#">
    <label for="ssn">Social Security Number:</label>
    <input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="Enter SSN" required>

    <div class="error" id="ssnError"></div>

    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>

<script>
    document.getElementById('ssnForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventDefault();

        const ssn = document.getElementById('ssn').value;
        const ssnError = document.getElementById('ssnError');

        // Simple validation: SSN should be 9 digits
        if (!/^\d{9}$/.test(ssn)) {
            ssnError.textContent = "Invalid SSN. Please enter exactly 9 digits.";
            return;
        }

        // Sanitize and validate (e.g., using parameterized queries)
        // Note: This is a placeholder for actual backend validation
        ssnError.textContent = "";
        alert("SSN submitted successfully!");
        // Here you would typically send the SSN to the server for further processing
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**:
   - The form includes a label and an input field for the social security number.
   - A submit button to submit the form.
   - An error message section to display validation errors.

2. **CSS Styling**:
   - Basic styling to make the form visually appealing and easy to use.
   - Error messages are styled in red to draw attention.

3. **JavaScript Validation**:
   - The form submission is prevented using `event.preventDefault()`.
   - A simple regex validation checks if the entered SSN is exactly 9 digits.
   - If the SSN is invalid, an error message is displayed.
   - If valid, an alert is shown to indicate success (this would typically be replaced with actual server-side processing).

This form provides a basic example of how to prompt for and validate a social security number securely. For production environments, you would need to integrate backend validation and encryption mechanisms.

